description.text: No matter what I tried I kept getting the pla plug between my bowden and brass tube. Eventually, taking everything apart I sheered my tube off inside the peek, and had to find a replacement. I'm now using this with 0 issues since: http://www.makergear.com/products/groovemounts

This will require a little bit of sanding on your machine to make the groovemount from makergear fit. I initially put everything together using spare wood left over from building my ultimaker. I then printed up some nicer looking more permanent parts. If you don't have Owen's bowden clamp I highly suggest printing it and having it on hand for when you make the switch.

  • Print the hotendHolder.stl

  • Print the newHotEndSpacer.stl

  • Slide the groovemount onto the hotendHolder and then assemble the hot end as usual. (you will probably have to sand the 8a wooden panels in order for the groovemount to fit properly.)

  • Attach Owen's Bowden clamp and run the Bowden down flush against the groovemount. (you may have to run filiment through the Bowden and into the groovemount and then push the Bowden down using the filiment as a guide)

  • Place the spacer between the groovemount and the aluminum plate then tighten everything down with the four thumb as you normally would.
    • I'm not very good with technical directions so if anything needs clarified just let me know and I'll do my best to help.

description.text: Geometric bowls created by students in 8th grade computer science class.
An IR remote control reflector for vertically mounted Apple TV's.  Works great with the Apple TV wall mount thing.

One of the first things I printed for my Apple TV was the 100mm VESA wall mount http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:14598 - I then screwed this into the wall, and it worked okay for the most part, but I found myself lying in bed, aiming the remote all over trying to get a good control signal. I decided to try making a reflector to rest on top - I wanted it simple and light - something I could fasten easily with a little lightweight double-sided tape. I then designed this in Google Sketchup and exported it to STL using one of the plugins. I figured that in the worst case, I'd want to print the primary reflecting surface facing down somehow, but then figured that I could just stick on some tinfoil to be the reflector - turns out the clear stuff reflects IR brilliantly, and no reflective surface was needed. I printed this on my RepRap (LM8UU) with a .5 Budhaschnozzle 1.1 using 3mm clear PLA with a fan @ 235C. Sliced it with Slic3r on my Mac using .25mm slices and printed it on a 60C bed covered with Kapton tape. Had to clean up the edges at the top at the end of printing, but otherwise it was perfect - small details at that temp are tough, but it worked out well enough for me.

This is a mount that holds the bottom of a venetian blind from moving - if your blinds can use it.

My house is fairly old, and on my back door there's a venetian blind that's mounted on the inside of the door.  The brackets that hold it down are what the blind came with, and about a year ago one broke and it was old enough that I couldn't find one, or never really looked when I was at home depot.
So then I remembered one day while letting the dogs out, and I went and retrieved the one good mount I had, and I built it up in Sketchup and printed a replacement.
When I first started printing this, I hadn't yet done PLA with a fan, however, we were having a December cold snap (I'm in Colorado) and I took my little floor heater and put it up on the table, having read that it can help.
This latest revision is a complete perfect copy of the original, however, to get all the details you'll have to print it in PLA, hot, and use a fan.
In my setup, I ran this PLA at 225C and sliced it using Slic3r at .25 per slice.  A fan is mandatory to get the top details on this.

title: Serpentine Celtic Knot Drop Spindle Whorl

description.text: ~12g whorl, 2.75" diameter with notch and dowel insert. This is light enough to spin extremely fine fiber by hand, as seen in the last photo with 21 micron merino wool.

Printer:

Maker Select 3D Printer v2

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

15%

Notes:

Printed weight is only about 13 grams including braces, raft and supports--extremely light, perfect for spinning lace and cobweb weight yarn.

gcode prints vertically on a small raft with built-in braces that easily break away by hand, and supports through the dowel rod hole that are easily chipped out.

Tools Required

  • 1 hook
  • Power drill with bit correctly sized for hook
  • 1 dowel rod, .31" in diameter

The cone sticking out of the center is where your hook will go. I've cut that off my finished product, drilled down into the dowel from the top of the whorl, and then hand-screwed in the hook. No glue required!

This design was inspired by one found in the Book of Kells and only slightly redesigned for this purpose. Re-illustrated in the book Celtic Art - The Methods of Construction by George Bain, this is Plate 6 of Page 111. I scanned this image and ran it through Adobe Illustrator and laid out the patterns how I wanted them for the whorl top, traced in SketchUp and built the body.

When I checked in my slicer, it was going to weigh somewhere around 38 grams, so I imported it into TinkerCAD (after first converting to STL in Blender from OBJ, cause I still haven't figured out how to design anything in Blender) and cut out tubes from the bottom, which helped significantly.

I began test printing it vertically because the time was reduced to about half of what it would have been lying flat, and the bottom of the round was chunky, so we stopped it and I built in the curved braces here. It worked great.

This is only for people who want to print really fast ;) Its use is shown in this video:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cSBqBW1w2wE This is the filament drive mechanism end of the Bowden extruder. The same coupling could be used on the other end (the extrusion, or hot end), or a special purpose (smaller) coupling could be designed to fit your specific extruder (one that also clamps the heater insulator). The idea of turning a nut onto the PTFE tube comes from profounddevices. I really liked it so much that I replaced my previous design to incorporate this idea. I\'m thinking of using the nut as part of an electrical switch to get feedback of when the pressure is fully released. This way you can put reversing functionality in the firmware without needing to configure it per material. The concept of using a Bowden cable as guide was suggested and pioneered by Ed Sells. See his post here:
blog.reprap.org/2009/04/bowden-extruder-concept.html If you can print to high tolerances or don't mind some trial and error prints, you can use a 'push to fit' variant of this coupling:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3775

• Start printing the part.
  • Screw nuts onto the ends of the PTFE tube (see parts list). If needed, cut a little material away from at the end of the tube to make it fit.
  • If your filaments do not run through easily anymore, run a 3mm drill through the end where you have the nut.
  • If you want it to be able to stand more force, put a drop of super glue on the PTFE (above the nut) and screw the nut a bit further. Then truncate the PTFE to be flush with the nut.
  • Push it into the printed part.

comments.text:
Upside down works fine. The overhang is chosen to be 45 degrees, for most machines (depending on nozzle shape, layer height, speed, filament, etc.) this is on the safe side of what can be done. You can go further by choosing a low-layer height, or extrude an inner shell first and then pasting the outline against it.
I've been able to makes some 90' overhangs, gravity hardly has an impact on what can be built, it's more how the nozzle tends to push material outward.
